elements.content: The 1:1 assembly reaction of the racemic form of the cross-linking ligand complex Na­[CuIILdpen(1R2R/1S2S)] with LnIII(NO3)3·6H2O gave the centrosymmetric circular (CuIILnIII)2 complex [CuIILdpen(1R2R/1S2S)LnIII(NO3)2]2 (1Ln: Ln = Gd, Tb, Dy), while the reaction of the enantiopure form Na­[CuIILdpen(1R2R)] with LnIII(NO3)3·6H2O gave the chiral chainlike (CuIILnIII)1∞ complex [CuIILdpen(1R2R)LnIII(NO3)2(CH3CN)]1∞·CH3CN (2Ln: Ln = Gd, Tb, Dy), where {CuIILdpen(1R2R)}− is (N-((1R,2R)-2-(((E)-3-ethoxy-2-oxybenzylidene)­amino)-1,2-diphenylethyl)-2-oxybenzamide)­copper­(II) and {CuIILdpen(1R2R/1S2S)}− is the racemic mixture of {CuIILdpen(1R2R)}− and {CuIILdpen(1S2S)}−. The copper­(II) component functions as a cross-linking ligand complex and bridges two LnIII ions at two phenoxo oxygen atoms and one ethoxy oxygen atom, as well as at an amido oxygen atom. For 1Ln, two binuclear species of [CuIILdpen(1R2R)LnIII(NO3)2] and [CuIILdpen(1S2S)LnIII(NO3)2] with opposite chiralities are linked by two amido oxygen atoms O3 and O3* to form a centrosymmetric circular structure with Gd–Cu = 3.370(1) Å and Gd–Cu* = 5.627(1) Å. For 2Ln, binuclear species with the same chirality are bridged by Gd–O3* = 2.228(5) Å to form a chiral chainlike structure with Gd–Cu = 3.3348(9) Å and Gd–Cu* = 6.2326(9) Å. The bridged angles through the amido group of Gd–O3*C7* are 133.9(5) and 177.6(4)° for 1Gd and 2Gd, respectively. The magnetic susceptibilities of 1Gd and 2Gd were analyzed by the spin-only Hamiltonian on the basis of the circular tetranuclear (−CuIIGdIII−)2 and linear chainlike (−CuIIGdIII−)1∞ structures, respectively. The CuII–GdIII magnetic interactions through two phenoxo bridges and a three-atom N–CO bridge, J 1 and J 2, are both ferromagnetic to be J 1 = +4.6 cm–1 and J 2 = +1.8 cm–1 for 1Gd and J 1 = +4.2 cm–1 and J 2 = +0.037 cm–1 for 2Gd. The J 2 value of 2Gd is much smaller than that of 1Gd. When the temperature was lowered, 1Ln and 2Ln (Ln = Tb, Dy) showed a decrease in the χM T vs T plot due to crystal field effects on the LnIII ion (Stark splitting) and an increase due to the ferromagnetic CuII–LnIII interaction. The magnetization values of 1Ln and 2Ln (Ln = Tb, Dy) without liquid paraffin are considerably larger than the corresponding values with liquid paraffin, indicating the presence of strong magnetic anisotropy. 1Tb and 1Dy showed frequency dependence of ac magnetic susceptibility under zero external dc magnetic field, showing the behavior of single-molecule magnets (SMMs). 2Tb and 2Dy showed no frequency dependence under a zero external magnetic field but showed a meaningful frequency dependence under an external magnetic field. Their energy barriers, Δ/k B, estimated by the Arrhenius plots are 29.4(6) and 20.6(3) K for 1Tb and 2Tb under dc bias fields of 0 and 1000 Oe, respectively, and those of 1Dy and 2Dy are 13.1(9) K and 16.4(2) K under dc bias fields of 0 and 1000 Oe, respectively.

Introduction

The self-assembly reaction has been applied for the formation of supramolecules and multidimensional materials. Molecular-based magnets have been successfully synthesized by the assembly reaction of multicomponents, which have donor and acceptor coordination abilities. The donor and acceptor components have magnetic moments, and the magnetic interaction between them extends to the supramolecule or dimensional lattice, depending on the nature of the magnetic interaction and the assembly manner, to produce various molecular-based magnetic materials. The representative molecular-based magnets MnCu(pba)(H2O)3⋅2H2O, MnCu(pbaOH)(H2O)3 (pba = 1,3-propylenebis(oxamato) and pbaOH = 2-hydroxy-1,3-propylenebis(oxamato)), Mn(hfa)2NIT-R (hfa = hexafluoroacetylacetonato and NIT-R (R = isopropyl, phenyl) = 2-R-4,4,5,5-tetramethyl-4,5-dihydro-1H-imidazoyl-1-oxy 3-oxide), [Fe(Me5C5)2]⋅+[TCNE]⋅-⋅MeCN ([Fe(Me5C5)2]⋅+ = decamethylferrocenium, [TCNE]⋅- = tetracyanoethenide), NBu4[MIICrIII(ox)3] (NBu4 = tetra-n-butylammonium, MII = Mn2+, Fe2+, Co2+, Ni2+, Cu2+, Zn2+), and [{FeIII(CN)6} n {MnIII(BS)} m ] x- ((n, m) = (1, 1), (1, 2), (1, 4); BS = N2O2 salen-type Schiff base ligand) are all synthesized by the assembly reaction of the donor and acceptor components. The assembly structure involving the donor/acceptor ratio depends on the selection of the proper components, in which the stereochemistry and the electronic effects by modifications of the ligand and metal ions can result in different assembly structures. There are many cases in which the steric effect from the substituent of the ligand produces different assembly structures. For example, (1) the isopropyl and phenyl substituents of Mn(hfa)2NIT-R give 1D and cyclic hexanuclear structures, respectively, and (2) the methyl and the phenyl substituents in [CuIILR] (LR = N-(2-R-imidazol-4-ylmethylidene)-2-aminoethylpyridine, R = methyl, phenyl) give cyclic tetranuclear and hexanuclear structures, respectively. The chirality must be a relevant element to generate a definitely different assembly structure, as exemplified by spontaneous resolution of tartaric acid salts. However, there are only a few examples in which the chirality of the component produces different assembly structures in the molecular-based magnet. In addition to the assembly structure, the chirality in the molecular-based magnets has attracted much attention recently in evolving new functions, such as nonlinear magnetic properties and chiral magnetic effects.

elements.content: In this study, we report that chiral discriminative assembly reactions of racemic and chiral CuII complexes with LnIII(NO3)3·6H2O (LnIII = GdIII, TbIII, DyIII) produce distinctly different structures: the centrosymmetric circular (CuIILnIII)2 structure of [CuIILdpen(1R2R/1S2S)LnIII(NO3)2]2·(solvent) (1Gd, 1Tb, 1Dy) and the chiral 1D (CuIILnIII)1∞ structure of [CuIILdpen(1R2R)LnIII(NO3)2(CH3CN)]1∞·CH3CN (2Gd, 2Tb, 2Dy). The synthetic procedure of the ligands and the assembly reactions of the CuII complexes with LnIII(NO3)3·6H2O are shown in and . The CuII component has a magnetic moment due to the S = 1/2 spin state of its d9 electronic configuration. The LnIII ions used in this study are GdIII, TbIII, and DyIII, and they have large magnetic moments due to their ground states: GdIII (4f 7, J = 7/2, S = 7/2, L = 0, 8S7/2), TbIII (4f 8, J = 6, S = 3, L = 3, 7F6), and DyIII (4f 9, J = 15/2, S = 5/2, L = 5, 6H15/2). Magnetic interaction can occur between CuII and LnIII ions through phenoxo and amido groups. For CuIILnIII complexes (LnIII = GdIII, TbIII, DyIII), it has been shown that ferromagnetic interaction through various bridging groups is operating. Therefore, it is anticipated that the magnetic interaction occurs in the supramolecule or crystal lattice, depending on the assembly structure, to give molecular-based magnets. While the GdIII ion is magnetically isotropic due to the ground state of GdIII (4f 7, J = 7/2, S = 7/2, L = 0, 8S7/2), the TbIII and DyIII ions have large magnetic anisotropy due to the ground states of TbIII (4f 8, J = 6, S = 3, L = 3, 7F6) and DyIII (4f 9, J = 15/2, S = 5/2, L = 5, 6H15/2). Since the discovery of single-molecule magnets (SMMs) in a Mn12 cluster in 1993, many synthetic designs for SMMs have been developed on the basis of d cluster molecules, mononuclear and polynuclear f complexes, and d–f complexes. A high-spin ground state and large magnetic anisotropy are required for the synthetic design of SMMs. Thus, it is anticipated that CuII–LnIII complexes with LnIII = TbIII, DyIII would exhibit SMM behaviors. Two pairs of CuII–LnIII complexes with circular and chainlike structures, 1Tb, 2Tb and 1Dy, 2Dy, would be good candidates for SMMs and single-chain magnets (SCMs). We report the synthesis, structures, and magnetic properties of these complexes.

elements.content: The racemic and optically pure N2O2 ligands H3Ldpen(1R2R/1S2S), H3Ldpen(1R2R), and H3Ldpen(1S2S) were prepared by a two-step reaction via intermediate compounds, according to the synthetic scheme shown in , where H3Ldpen(1R2R) is an abbreviation of the chiral N2O2 ligand N-((1R,2R)-2-(((E)-3-ethoxy-2-hydroxybenzylidene)­amino)-1,2-diphenylethyl)-2-hydroxybenzamide, H3Ldpen(1S2S) denotes its 1S,2S form, and H3Ldpen(1R2R/1S2S) is the racemic ligand. In the first step of the synthesis of the racemic ligand H3Ldpen(1R2R/1S2S), the 1:1 condensation product of phenyl salicylate and a racemic mixture of (1R,2R/1S,2S)-1,2-diphenylethanediamine, i.e., N-((1R,2R/1S,2S)-2-amino-1,2-diphenylethyl)-2-hydroxybenzamide, was obtained as an intermediate compound. The 1:1 product was reacted with 3-ethoxysalicylaldehyde in a 1:1 molar ratio to give the tetradentate ligand H3Ldpen(1R2R/1S2S) as a yellow crystalline material. The chiral tetradentate ligands H3Ldpen(1R2R) and H3Ldpen(1S2S) were similarly synthesized using (1R,2R)-1,2-diphenylethylenediamine and (1S,2S)-1,2-diphenylethylenediamine, respectively.

elements.content: The racemic CuII complex Na­[CuIILdpen(1R2R/1S2S)]·(solvent) was synthesized by mixing the racemic ligand H3Ldpen(1R2R/1S2S), copper­(II) acetate monohydrate and NaOH in a 1:1:3 molar ratio in methanol. The resulting crude product was recrystallized from a mixed solution of acetonitrile and a small amount of ethanol to precipitate deep red block crystals with the formula Na­[CuIILdpen(1R2R/1S2S)]·CH3CN, as confirmed by X-ray structural analysis. The crystals exhibited efflorescence to eliminate the acetonitrile molecule and partially absorb the moisture under the open atmosphere, giving the product with the chemical formula Na­[CuIILdpen(1R2R/1S2S)]·H2O·0.5CH3CN. The elemental analysis agrees with the formula, and the detailed efflorescence process was confirmed by TGA analysis (Figure S1 in the Supporting Information). TGA analysis detected weight loss corresponding to H2O·0.5CH3CN, and this result agrees with the elemental analysis. The optically pure complex Na­[CuIILdpen(1R2R)]·(solvent) was synthesized by mixing the optically pure H3Ldpen(1R2R), copper­(II) acetate monohydrate, and NaOH in a 1:1:3 molar ratio in methanol. The resulting crude product was recrystallized from a mixed solution of acetonitrile and a small amount of ethanol to obtain deep red block crystals with the formula Na­[CuIILdpen(1R2R)]·2CH3CN, which was confirmed by X-ray structural analysis. The crystals exhibited efflorescence to eliminate the acetonitrile molecule and absorb the moisture under an open atmosphere, giving the product with the chemical formula Na­[CuIILdpen(1R2R)]·H2O, which agrees with the elemental analysis. The detailed efflorescence process was confirmed by TGA analysis (Figure S1). TGA analysis detected weight loss corresponding to H2O.

elements.content: a shows the plots of χM T versus T. The χM T values at 300 K are 12.75 and 12.31 cm3 K mol–1 for 1Tb and 2Tb, respectively. These are slightly larger than the value of 12.19 cm3 K mol–1 expected for noninteracting ions of CuII (S = 1/2) and TbIII (4f 8, J = 6, S = 3, L = 3, 7F6) with g Cu = 2 and g J = 3/2. When the temperature is lowered, the χM T value decreases, reaching the shallow bottoms of 12.29 cm3 K mol–1 at 80 K and 10.30 cm3 K mol–1 at 30 K, and then increases to 21.53 and 15.69 cm3 K mol–1 at 1.9 K for 1Tb and 2Tb, respectively. The decrease is mainly due to the crystal field effect on the TbIII ion (Stark splitting), while the increase in the χM T value at the low-temperature region can be ascribed to weak intramolecular CuII–TbIII ferromagnetic interactions. Two kinds of magnetic interactions between CuII and TbIII ions can be identified in both 1Tb and 2Tb: the J 1 of intradimer interaction via two phenoxo bridges and a supposedly weaker J 2 of interdimer interaction via an amido bridge. At present, magnetic calculations have not been applied to estimate the magnetic coupling constants due to the intrinsic magnetic anisotropy of the TbIII ion. The distinctly different magnetic profiles in the χM T versus T plots can be mainly ascribed to the difference in the interdimer magnetic interactions via the amido bridge for the two compounds. The limited decrease in χM T with respect to the room-temperature value and the steep increase below 80 K suggest that, for 1Tb, both J 1 and J 2 are positive. In contrast, the more discernible decrease in χM T and the modest increase only below 30 K suggest that, for the 1D complex 2Tb, J 1 is significantly positive, while J 2 is very weak or even negligible. This difference could be related to the different bridging geometries observed in the X-ray structure analyses: Tb–O3*–C7* = 138.82(12) and 177.0(3)° (asterisks indicate the corresponding atoms of the neighboring dimeric unit) for 1Tb and 2Tb, respectively.

elements.content: The field-dependent magnetizations from 0 to 5 T were measured at 1.9 K by using samples with and without liquid paraffin, and the results are shown in b in the form of M/Nβ versus H plots, where the magnetization is the value per CuTb. elements.content: Dynamic properties of 1Tb and 2Tb were examined by ac magnetic susceptibility measurements at frequencies of 10–10000 Hz (10, 21, 46, 100, 215, 464, 1000, 1291, 1668, 2154, 2782, 3593, 4641, 5994, 7742, and 10000 Hz) as a function of temperature at 2–10 K. 1Tb showed a frequency dependence of ac magnetic susceptibility, and the maximums of χM′ and χM″ were observed under zero external dc magnetic field (a (left)). This indicates relatively slow relaxation of magnetization. The Arrhenius plot shows a straight line for the χM″ peak (), and the activation energy (Δ) for the magnetization reversal under zero magnetic field was estimated as Δ/k B = 29.4(6) K with τ0 = [1.5(3)] × 10–8 s, where τ0 stands for the pre-exponential factor in the Arrhenius equation: ln­(2πν) = −ln τ0 – Δ/k B T. The Cole–Cole analysis was performed for 1Tb using the above ac susceptibilities and the equation χ­(ω) = χS + (χT – χS)/(1 + (iωτ)1−α), where χT and χS are the isothermal and adiabatic magnetic susceptibilities, respectively. The plot draws a partial semicircle (Figure S4 in the Supporting Information), and the optimized α value was 0.093(3) at 3.0 K. This finding indicates a relaxation process operative in 1Tb. 2Tb showed only a slight χM″ without any external dc field (b (left)), but the frequency dependence of ac magnetic susceptibility was pronounced under an external magnetic field of 1000 Oe (b (right)). From these data, it can be concluded that the Arrhenius plot exhibited a straight line (), and the parameters were estimated as Δ/k B = 20.6(3) K and τ0 = [2.9(3)] × 10–9 s for 2Tb. The Cole–Cole analysis gave a semicircle Figure S4), and the optimized α value was determined to be 0.39(1) at 2.0 K. Here, the external field was applied only for suppressing the zero-field quantum tunneling of magnetization (QTM).

elements.content: The assembly structures of copper­(II) components of chiral and racemic ligands (H3Ldpen(1R2R), H3Ldpen(1R2R/1S2S)) with Na+ and LnIII salts (LnIII = GdIII, TbIII, DyIII) were studied. The copper­(II) component species {CuIILdpen(1R2R)}− ((N-((1R,2R)-2-(((E)-3-ethoxy-2-oxybenzylidene)­amino)-1,2-diphenylethyl)-2-oxybenzamide)­copper­(II)) functions as a “cross-linking ligand complex” at the two phenoxo oxygen atoms and the amido oxygen atom. A chiral CuII complex involving a Na+ ion, [(CH3CN)­NaCuIILdpen(1R2R)]1∞, has a chainlike structure, and within a chain, two adjacent molecules with the same chirality are linked by a Na+ ion to form a homochiral chain structure. The assembly reaction of the racemic mixture {CuIILdpen(1R2R/1S2S)}− and Na+ ion in CH3CN generates a homochiral chainlike structure, and two chains with opposite chiralities of [(CH3CN)­NaCuIILdpen(1R2R)]1∞ and [(CH3CN)­NaCuIILdpen(1S2S)]1∞ coexist in a crystal. This demonstrates that the assembly of racemic species and Na+ ion gives the same assembly structure as that of the chiral species. The 1:1 assembly reaction of the racemic form of the “cross-linking ligand complex” Na­[CuIILdpen(1R2R/1S2S)] and LnIII(NO3)3·6H2O gave the centrosymmetric circular (CuIILnIII)2 complex [CuIILdpen(1R2R/1S2S)LnIII(NO3)2]2 (1Ln), while the reaction of the enantiopure form Na­[CuIILdpen(1R2R)] and LnIII(NO3)3·6H2O gave the chiral chainlike (CuIILnIII)1∞ complex [CuIILdpen(1R2R)LnIII(NO3)2(CH3CN)]1∞·CH3CN (2Ln). The magnetic susceptibilities of 1Gd and 2Gd were analyzed by the spin-only Hamiltonian on the basis of the circular tetranuclear (−CuIIGdIII−)2 and linear chain (−CuIIGdIII−)1∞ structures, respectively. The CuII–GdIII magnetic interaction through two phenoxo bridges and a three-atom N–CO bridge, J 1 and J 2, are both ferromagnetic, and the magnitude of the J 2 value of 2Gd is extremely smaller than that of 1Gd. The magnetic susceptibility data of 1Ln and 2Ln (Ln = Tb, Dy) showed the crystal field effect on the LnIII ion (Stark splitting). The magnetic properties of 2Tb and 2Dy are ascribed to a dimeric unit described as SMM, as the interdimer CuII-LnIII magnetic interaction via the amido group should be negligibly small due to the substantially different structural geometry at the part from 1Tb and 1Dy. The magnetizations of 1Ln and 2Ln (Ln = Tb, Dy) without liquid paraffin are steeper and considerably larger than the corresponding values with liquid paraffin, indicating the presence of strong magnetic anisotropy. 1Tb and 1Dy showed frequency dependence of ac magnetic susceptibility under zero external dc magnetic field, indicating the behavior of SMMs. 2Tb and 2Dy showed no frequency dependence under zero external magnetic field but showed a meaningful frequency dependence under an external magnetic field. Their energy barriers of slow magnetic relaxation, Δ/k B, estimated by the Arrhenius plots are 29.4(6) and 20.6(3) K for 1Tb and 2Tb under dc bias fields of 0 and 1000 Oe, respectively, and those of 1Dy and 2Dy are 13.1(9) and 16.4(2) K under dc bias fields of 0 and 1000 Oe, respectively. Although the activation energies of the magnetization reversal are comparable between 1Ln and 2Ln, the tunneling efficiencies at the zero dc bias are quite different. Namely, 1Tb and 1Dy showed appreciable frequency dependent ac susceptibilities at zero dc bias field, while 2Tb and 2Dy required a bias field to slow down magnetization reorientation ( and ). The CuIILnIII dinuclear moiety alone is responsible for the SMM behavior observed, and the bulky ligands and counteranions may play the role of an arranger of the CuIILnIII packing motifs. The present work clarified that the racemic and enantiopure forms of the ligands were successfully applied to the construction of SMM solids, affording 1Tb and 1Dy with the centrosymmetric monoclinic space group P21/n and 2Tb and 2Dy with the noncentrosymmetric orthorhombic space group P212121. The magnetic easy axes of the LnIII ions are completely parallel within a molecule in the former, because of the molecular inversion symmetry. On the other hand, the repeating CuIILnIII units are arrayed in a 21 screw fashion in the latter, inevitably giving rise to the large canting of the LnIII easy axes between any neighboring units. Parallel easy-axis arrangement is suitable not only for the SMM prerequisites, a large spin ground state and a large axial anisotropy, but also for the reduction of the efficiency of the tunneling mechanism. There have been many reports on the SMM having centrosymmetry, including N2 3–-bridged dinculear LnIII complexes. In this context, the use of chiral/achiral/racemic ligands regulating the presence and absence of symmetry elements would afford much valuable information in an SMM mechanistic investigation.

The racemic and optically pure tetradentate N2O2 ligands H3Ldpen(1R2R/1S2S), H3Ldpen(1R2R), and H3Ldpen(1S2S) were prepared by a two-step reaction procedure via an intermediate product.

<italic>N</italic>-((1<italic>R</italic>,2<italic>R</italic>/<italic>1S</italic>,2<italic>S</italic>)-2-Amino-1,2-diphenylethyl)-2-hydroxybenzamide

This intermediate product was synthesized as follows. (1R,2R)-1,2-Diphenylethylenediamine (1.27 g, 6.0 mmol), (1S,2S)-1,2-diphenylethylenediamine (1.27 g, 6.0 mmol), and phenyl salicylate (2.57 g, 12 mmol) were mixed in a mortar and well ground to be a paste. The magnetic behaviors of 1Gd and 2Gd are shown as the plots of χM T versus T and 1/χM versus T in a, where χM is the molar magnetic susceptibility per CuIIGdIII and T is the absolute temperature. The χM T values for 1Gd and 2Gd at 300 K are 8.84 and 8.37 cm3 K mol–1, respectively. These values are comparable to each other and are slightly larger than the calculated value of 8.25 cm3 K mol–1 expected for one CuII (S = 1/2) and one GdIII (4f7, J = 7/2, L = 0, S = 7/2, 8S7/2) noninteracting ion. The plots of 1/χM versus T for 1Gd and 2Gd follow the Curie–Weiss equation 1/χM = (T – Θ)/C, with Weiss constants of Θ = +2.8 K and Θ = +3.0 K, respectively, clearly indicating ferromagnetic interaction.

The profiles of χM T versus T plots of 2Gd show a significant difference from 1Gd in the lowest-temperature region. The χM T value of 2Gd increases monotonically to become 20.65 cm3 K mol–1 at 1.9 K. The increase in the χM T value indicates the occurrence of a ferromagnetic interaction between CuII and GdIII ions. The largest value of χM T = 20.65 cm3 mol–1 K at 1.9 K is larger than that of 9.85 cm3 mol–1 K expected for an S = 4 spin state resulting from ferromagnetic coupling between CuII (S = 1/2) and GdIII (S = 7/2) in a dinuclear CuII–GdIII unit and is even larger than the 18.0 cm3 mol–1 K expected for an S = 8 × 1/2 spin state in a ferromagnetically coupled tetranuclear CuII–GdIII–CuII–GdIII unit.
